Package interactr.cs.kuleuven.be.purecollections

Class PMap<K,V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • interactr.cs.kuleuven.be.purecollections.PMap<K,V>
  • Type Parameters:
    K - the type of keys
    V - the type of values
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.util.Map<K,V>

    public abstract class PMap<K,V>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.Map<K,V>
    A purely functional map.

    Instances of this class are immutable. This class' implementations of the mutator methods of the Map interface are deprecated and throw UnsupportedOperationException.

    Functional counterparts of the mutator methods:

    map.put(k, v);map = map.plus(k, v);
    map.putAll(m);map = map.plusAll(m);
    map.remove(k);map = map.minus(k);

    There is only one empty instance of this class. It is returned by static method PMap.empty().

    To turn any Map m into a PMap, write PMap.empty().plusAll(m).

    Null keys or values are not allowed.

    We say a map is well-hashed if the hash function disperses the elements properly, i.e. if the log(n) least significant bits of the elements' hash codes are distinct. Most operations are O(log(n)) if the map is well-hashed, and O(n) otherwise. The documentation for each operation specifies the time complexity for well-hashed maps and for non-well-hashed maps, in that order, if different.

    This class assumes that each object's hashCode() method is consistent with its equals() method, i.e. if o1.equals(o2), then o1.hashCode() == o2.hashCode().

      • equals

        public boolean equals​(java.lang.Object other)
        Returns true iff the specified object is a Map and its size equals this map's size and for each of this map's entries, the specified map contains an entry whose key and value are equal.

        Complexity: If the specified object is a PMap, and either this map or the specified map is well-hashed: O(n); if neither map is well-hashed: O(n^2). If the specified object is not a PMap, then O(n * c), where c is the cost of the entry set's contains method.

        Specified by:
        equals in interface java.util.Map<K,V>
        Overrides:
        equals in class java.lang.Object
